Ce que je dis à mes amis non-américains
CAMBRIDGE – Je voyage souvent à l'étranger et mes amis étrangers demandent à chaque fois, avec des degrés de perplexité divers : mais que se passe-t-il donc dans votre pays ?
Voici ce que je leur réponds.
Premièrement, prenez garde à ne pas faire de contresens sur les élections de 2016.
Contrairement à certains commentaires, le système politique américain n'a pas été balayé par une vague de populisme.
It is true that we have a long history of rebellion against elites.
Donald Trump tapped into the vein of a tradition associated with leaders like Andrew Jackson and William Jennings Bryan in the 19th century and Huey Long and George Wallace in the 20th century.
And yet Trump fell short of winning the popular vote by nearly three million votes.
He won the election by appealing to populist resentment in three Rust Belt states (Michigan, Pennsylvania, and Wisconsin), which had previously voted for the Democratic Party.
If a hundred thousand votes had been cast differently in these states, Trump would have lost the Electoral College and the presidency.
That said, Trump's victory raises the real issue of the rise in social and regional inequalities in the United States.
The latest bestseller by J.D. Vance, Hillbilly Elegy, convincingly describes the significant difference between California and the Appalachians.
Research conducted by Princeton economists Anne Case and Angus Deaton shows that demographic trends among white non-college graduates are worse than those of African Americans, who historically occupied the lower end of inequality.
In 1999, mortality rates among whites without higher education were around 30% below those of African Americans; by 2015, they were 30% higher.
Furthermore, employment in the industrial sector, which was once one of the main sources of high-wage jobs for white working-class people, has significantly declined over the last generation, now accounting for only 2% of the workforce.
These former Democratic voters were seduced by Trump's promises to change things and bring jobs back to the industrial sector.
Paradoxically, Trump's efforts to repeal President Barack Obama's healthcare legislation risk making their lives even harder.
The second thing I tell my foreign friends is that one should not underestimate Trump's communication skills.
Many people are shocked by his rages on Twitter and his scandalous disregard for facts.
But Trump is a veteran of reality television, where he learned that the key to success is monopolizing viewers' attention, and that the best way to do so is to make extreme statements, without worrying about the truth.
Twitter allows him to set his agenda and distract from his critics.
What annoys commentators in the media and academic circles does not bother his supporters.
But as soon as he moves from his self-centered permanent campaign to attempts at governing, Twitter becomes a double-edged sword that deters some allies whom he desperately needs.
Thirdly, I tell my friends not to expect normal behavior.
Normally, a president who loses the popular vote moves toward the political center in order to attract more support.
That is exactly what George W. Bush did successfully in 2001.
Trump, on the other hand, claims that he won the popular vote and acts as if that were truly the case, which pleases his base voters.
Although Trump made solid centrist appointments at the Departments of Defense, State, and Homeland Security, his choices for the Environmental Protection Agency and the Department of Health and Human Services are at the extremes of the Republican Party.
His White House staff is divided between ideologues and pragmatists — and he intends to please both camps at once.
Fourthly, one should not underestimate American institutions.
Sometimes my friends talk as if the sky is falling on their heads and ask me if Trump is a dangerous narcissist like Mussolini.
I tell them not to panic.
Although the United States has many problems, it is not the Italy of 1922.
Our national political elites are often polarized; but the founders of America were just as polarized.
In the design of the United States Constitution, the founders' goal was not to ensure that the government would be harmonious, but to limit political power to a system of checks and balances that makes the exercise of these powers difficult.
A joke about this says that the founders created a political system so that it would be impossible for King George to rule over us - impossible for him or for anyone else.
Inefficiency has been used in the service of liberty.
Trump's presidency is still in its early stages, and we cannot be certain what might happen after, say, a major terrorist attack.
So far, however, the courts, Congress, and the states have safeguarded this balance of power within the administration, as Madison intended.
And the permanent executive service officials still carry weight.
Finally, my friends ask what all this means for American foreign policy and for the liberal international order led by the United States since 1945.
Frankly, I don't know, but I am less worried about the rise of China than about the rise of Trump.
Although American leaders, including Obama, have complained about free riders, the United States has long taken the lead in providing important global public goods: security, a stable international reserve currency, relatively open markets, and the management of our planet's common resources.
Despite the problems with the international order under U.S. leadership, the world has prospered and poverty has been reduced under this order.
But no one can be certain that this will continue.
The United States will have to cooperate with China, Europe, Japan, and other countries to manage transnational problems.
During the 2016 campaign, Trump was the first candidate from a major party in 70 years to question the American alliance system.
Since taking office in January, statements by Trump and his members suggest that he may continue to do so.
The power to constrain and persuade the United States, after all, largely comes from the fact that the United States has 60 allies (while China has only a few).
But the stability of multilateral institutions, which help manage the global economy and the planet's common goods, is more uncertain.
Trump's Budget Director speaks of a budget of constraint, with budget cuts made to the State Department and to the United Nations system.
Other members of the government argue for replacing multilateral trade agreements with bilateral "fair and balanced" arrangements. Trump rejects Obama's efforts to address climate change.
I tell my friends that I would like to be able to reassure them on these issues.
But I cannot.
